We see how this changed the significance of home_shoton and home_corners. This will be the model forward realizing the significance level is 0.8.

BOOTSTRAPPING 
bs <- function(formula, data, indices){
  d <- data[indices, ] #allows boot to select sample
  fit <- lm(formula, data = d)
  return(coef(fit))
}
#Bootstrapping with 5000 replications
results <- boot(df, 
                statistic = bs,
                R = 5000,
                formula = formula(model3))

Print distributions with model3 values marked in red.

for(i in 1:length(results$t0)){
  hist(results$t[,i], 
       prob = TRUE,
       main = variable.names(model3)[i])
  abline(v = coefficients(model3)[i], col = 'red')#
}

SUMMARY

7 final parameters were found for the model. Looking at the distributions for the bootstrapped values showed that all parameters were likely. The coefficents were

coef(model3)

   (Intercept) home_team_goal        home_y1    home_shoton   home_corners     away_fouls      home_poss 
    3.19366015    -0.16243543     0.13442175    -0.03375885    -0.04168095    -0.03982536    -0.01622975

Our model shows that teams are more likely to have goals scored against them if they play aggressively (get yellow cards) and fail to retain the ball (negative coefficient for home_poss). Also, teams that fail to make it to the final part of the pitch to either have a shot on goal or receive a corner kick are more likely to have goals scored against them. However, these to variables were not found to be significant on a 95% level and therefore this finding may not hold.
